Determine: does the candidate text above come from a clause in the uploaded contract that covers the SAME SUBJECT the user is asking to draft (e.g., confidentiality, limitation of liability, indemnification, governing law, term and termination, payment terms)?

The candidate text may be a full clause OR only a partial excerpt — documents are split into chunks during indexing, so an indemnification clause may arrive as just its opening paragraph. Treat a partial excerpt as a duplicate when it clearly belongs to a clause on the user's topic, even if the excerpt alone does not cover every aspect of that topic.

Return JSON:
{
  "is_duplicate": true | false,
  "matched_title": "<the clause heading or an inferred short title, or null if not clearly headed>",
  "summary": "<2-3 sentence plain-English summary of what the matched clause does — scope, allocation of risk, notable carve-outs — or null when is_duplicate is false>"
}

Rules:
- Return TRUE for is_duplicate when the candidate text is substantively about the topic the user asked to draft, including when it is only an excerpt of such a clause.
- Return FALSE when the candidate text only mentions the topic in passing (e.g., a defined term reused in a different clause) or is clearly a different clause.
- If you can read a heading or clause title for the matching clause, populate matched_title. Otherwise return null.
- When is_duplicate is true, populate summary with 2-3 plain-English sentences covering: what the clause does (scope), who bears the obligation or risk, and any notable carve-outs or omissions a reader should know. Keep it readable by a non-lawyer; do not include legal jargon or copy verbatim from the clause.
- When is_duplicate is false, set summary to null.
- Return ONLY valid JSON. No prose.
